  "prompt": "Do satellites emit color when viewed in the night sky?",
  "response": "Satellites themselves do not emit light or color like a star or a planet; instead, they reflect sunlight. As a result, when viewed from Earth during the night, satellites appear as small points of light and can sometimes seem to have different colors due to atmospheric conditions, light pollution, and the angle of observation. However, this color is not inherent to the satellite itself but rather a result of the light it reflects and how that light interacts with the Earth's atmosphere. \n\nSome satellites may also have external lights or be equipped with different reflective materials that can create a variety of visual appearances, but generally, they mainly appear as white or yellowish points of light in the night sky.",
